# What is Block Level Storage
-> Block-level storage operates at the low-level (raw storage device level) and manages data as a set of numbered, fixed-size blocks.

Each block acts as an individual storage unit with its own address, and the operating system controls how these blocks are organized and used (for example, by formatting them with a file system like NTFS or ext4).

âš™ï¸ Example in AWS
When you attach an EBS volume to an EC2 instance, it provides block-level storage.
Your EC2 instanceâ€™s operating system formats it with a file system and treats it just like a physical hard disk.

In AWS, block-level storage is mainly provided by EBS (Elastic Block Store).

# What is EBS
-> EBS (Elastic Block Store) is a block-level storage service used to store data persistently for EC2 instances.
-> It acts like a virtual hard disk that you can attach or detach from an EC2 instance at any time.

ðŸ”¹ Key Points
EBS Attachment Limit:
You can attach up to 16 EBS volumes to a single EC2 instance (for most instance types; newer ones may support even more).

EBS Volume Size:
Each EBS volume can range from 1 GiB up to 64 TiB in size, depending on the volume type.

EBS Multi-Attach:
The EBS Multi-Attach feature allows a single EBS volume to be attached to multiple EC2 instances at the same time.
This is supported only on io1 or io2 volume types and must be in the same Availability Zone (AZ).
Useful for clustered or shared-data applications (e.g., high availability setups).

Hypervisor Support:
Xen Hypervisor: Older virtualization platform used by legacy EC2 instances. It does not support EBS Multi-Attach.
Nitro Hypervisor: Modern, high-performance hypervisor used by most current instance types. It supports EBS Multi-Attach, enhanced networking, and better performance.

ðŸ’¾ Types of Elastic Block Storage (EBS)
1ï¸âƒ£ SSD (Solid State Drive)
Provides faster performance compared to HDD.
Works based on IOPS (Input/Output Operations Per Second).
Ideal for transactional workloads such as databases and boot volumes.

2ï¸âƒ£ HDD (Hard Disk Drive)
Offers slower performance compared to SSD.
Works based on Throughput (data transfer rate).
Suitable for sequential workloads like big data, log processing, and backups.

3 Snapshot-based

âš™ï¸ SSD Types (IOPS-Based Performance)
1) General Purpose SSD
Volume types: gp2 and gp3
Use case: Balances price and performance for most workloads.
IOPS range: Minimum 100 to Maximum 16,000 IOPS
Volume size: 1 GiB to 16 TiB

ðŸ”¸ gp2
Default volume type when you create an EC2 instance.
Baseline: 3 IOPS per GiB of volume size.
Example: 8 GiB Ã— 3 = 24 IOPS, but AWS provides minimum 100 IOPS to ensure smooth performance.

To increase IOPS, you must increase the volume size (e.g., 100 GiB â†’ 300 IOPS).

ðŸ”¸ gp3
Newer generation general purpose SSD.
Baseline 3,000 IOPS (independent of volume size).
You can provision up to 16,000 IOPS and 1,000 MB/s throughput separately from storage capacity.

2) Provisioned IOPS SSD
Volume types: io1, io2, and io2 Block Express
Designed for I/O-intensive workloads such as databases (Oracle, SQL Server, etc.)
Volume size: 4 GiB to 16 TiB

ðŸ”¸ io1
Supports 100 to 64,000 IOPS
Supports Nitro-based instances only

ðŸ”¸ io2
Supports 100 to 64,000 IOPS
Provides higher durability (99.999%) than io1

Also works only with Nitro-based instances

ðŸ”¸ io2 Block Express
Supports more than 64,000 IOPS (up to 256,000 IOPS)
Designed for R5b instances and high-end workloads like large SAP or Oracle DBs.

âš™ï¸ HDD Types (Throughput-Based Performance)
1) st1 (Throughput Optimized HDD)
Volume size: 125 GiB to 16 TiB
Throughput: Up to 500 MB/s
Best for big data, data warehouses, log processing, and streaming workloads.

2) sc1 (Cold HDD)
Volume size: 125 GiB to 16 TiB
Throughput: Up to 250 MB/s
Best for infrequently accessed data with lowest cost.

âš¡ What is Throughput?
Throughput is the amount of data transferred successfully from one place to another within a specific time period.
It is usually measured in bits per second (bps) â€” such as Megabits per second (Mbps) or Gigabits per second (Gbps).

ðŸ§  Additional Notes
HDD volumes (st1, sc1) cannot be used as boot volumes â€” only SSD (gp2, gp3, io1, io2) volumes can.
Use HDD when your workload involves less frequent I/O operations but large amounts of data.
Use SSD when your workload requires fast and consistent I/O performance.


ðŸ”¹ What is an EBS Snapshot?
An EBS Snapshot is a point-in-time backup of your EBS volume, stored in Amazon S3 (managed internally by AWS).
It captures the exact state of your volume data at the time the snapshot is taken.

ðŸ”¹ Use Cases
Regular backups of production EBS volumes.
Disaster recovery (restore volumes in another region).
Template creation for launching pre-configured EC2 instances.
Migration between environments or AWS accounts.

ðŸ”¹ Storage Type
Although snapshots are stored in Amazon S3, they are not directly accessible like normal S3 objects.
AWS manages this storage internally â€” you cannot browse them in S3 buckets.
When you create a volume from a snapshot, AWS lazily loads data blocks (on-demand restore) for faster provisioning.


# Is it possible to reduce a EBS volume (Just read to get ne idea)
Yes, it is possible to reduce the size of an EBS volume in AWS, but with some limitations and considerations.

Hereâ€™s a breakdown of how it works:

1. For General Purpose SSD (gp3) and other EBS types:
Directly reducing the size of an EBS volume is not supported directly in AWS.
However, you can shrink the file system and then create a snapshot and restore the snapshot to a new, smaller volume.
Steps to reduce the size of an EBS volume:
Backup: Take a snapshot of the existing volume to prevent data loss.
Shrink the file system:
Log into your EC2 instance and reduce the file system size to fit within the desired new volume size.
For example, if you're using ext4 or xfs, you can resize the file system using commands like resize2fs for ext4.
Create a new volume: After shrinking the file system, create a new EBS volume with the desired smaller size.
Copy data: Mount the new volume and copy the data from the old (larger) volume to the new (smaller) one.
Detach the old volume: Once youâ€™ve confirmed everything is working properly on the new volume, you can detach the old volume.
2. Elastic Block Store Snapshots:
AWS allows you to take snapshots of volumes. When reducing the size of a volume, this snapshot is typically useful as a backup or to restore data if necessary.
Limitations and Considerations:
Data loss risk: If the volume is not properly resized before transferring data, you risk losing data that exceeds the new smaller volume's capacity.
Downtime: There may be some downtime during the resizing process since you will need to detach the old volume and attach the new one.
Volume type: This process is applicable to most volume types, but the exact steps may vary depending on the file system used and the operating system of your EC2 instance.
Alternative - Elastic File System (EFS):
If your use case involves frequent resizing and dynamic scaling, consider using Amazon EFS, which automatically scales up and down, eliminating the need to manually adjust volume sizes. However, EFS is not suitable for all workloads, especially those requiring block-level storage.

In summary, while direct reduction of EBS volume size isnâ€™t supported, the process of resizing can be achieved with a workaround involving shrinking the file system, creating a new volume, and transferring the data.



