# What is IP
-> IP stands for Internet Protocol.
-> It is used to communicate data between one system and another over a network.
-> Every device connected to a network is identified by a unique IP address.

# Types of IP Addresses
-> We have two main versions of IP:
-> IPv4 (Internet Protocol version 4)
-> IPv6 (Internet Protocol version 6)

# IPv4 (Internet Protocol Version 4)
-> Uses 32 bits to represent an address.
-> Written in decimal format (e.g., 192.168.0.1).
-> Supports around 4.3 billion unique addresses.
-> Contains both Public and Private IP ranges.

âœ… Example:
10.0.0.1, 172.16.0.5, 192.168.1.10

# IPv6 (Internet Protocol Version 6)
-> Uses 128 bits to represent an address.
-> Written in hexadecimal format (e.g., 2001:0db8:85a3:0000:0000:8a2e:0370:7334).
-> Provides a much larger address space (almost unlimited).
-> Mainly used as Public IP because itâ€™s designed for the modern internet.

ðŸ§  Note:
One IP address has 4 octets (in IPv4).
One octet = 8 bits.
Therefore, IPv4 = 4 Ã— 8 = 32 bits.
One byte = 8 bits.

| Type     | Bits    | Format            | Example     | Public/Private |
| -------- | ------- | ----------------- | ----------- | -------------- |
| **IPv4** | 32-bit  | Decimal (x.x.x.x) | 192.168.1.1 | Both           |
| **IPv6** | 128-bit | Hexadecimal       | 2001:db8::1 | Public only    |


# What is EIP (Elastic IP Address)
-> Elastic IP (EIP) is a static public IPv4 address in AWS that remains the same even if you stop or restart your EC2 instance, ensuring consistent connectivity.

# By default how many elastic ip address does AWS offer
-> Each AWS account is allowed to allocate up to 5 Elastic IPs in each Region.

# What is Static IP
-> It is a constant and permanent IP address.
-> It never changes even if you stop or restart the instance.
-> In AWS, a Static IP can be achieved using an Elastic IP (EIP).

# What is Dynamic IP
-> It is an IP address that changes automatically whenever you stop and restart the instance.
-> AWS assigns a new public IP from its pool each time the instance starts.

# What is VPC
-> VPC stands for Virtual Private Cloud in AWS.
-> It is a virtual network that you can create within AWS.
-> It allows you to control your own network environment, including IP ranges, subnets, route tables, and gateways.

ðŸ“˜ Note:
You can assign IP addresses to your VPC using CIDR blocks (Classless Inter-Domain Routing).

# Example CIDR Range
-> 10.0.0.0/16 â†’ This represents one IPv4 range.
-> Since IPv4 addresses are 32-bit, and we used /16,
    32 - 16 = 16 bits left for host addresses  
    2^16 = 65,536 total IPs (but 5 are reserved by AWS) 
-> So effectively, you get 65,531 usable IPs.
-> The /16 block is large, while /28 is the smallest allowed in AWS VPCs.

# CIDR Range Sizes
| CIDR | Available IPs | Notes                   |
| ---- | ------------- | ----------------------- |
| /16  | 65,536        | Largest VPC range       |
| /24  | 256           | Commonly used           |
| /28  | 16            | Smallest allowed in AWS |

AWS does not allow CIDR smaller than /28 (like /29, /30, etc.).
Most common VPC CIDRs are /16 and /24.

# By default how many Ip address does aws reserve in AWS
-> When you create any subnet in AWS, 5 IP addresses are reserved by AWS and cannot be used by you

| IP Type               | Example (for subnet 10.0.0.0/24) | Why Reserved                        |
| --------------------- | -------------------------------- | ----------------------------------- |
| **Network Address**   | 10.0.0.0                         | Identifies the subnet itself        |
| **VPC Router**        | 10.0.0.1                         | Reserved for internal routing       |
| **DNS Server**        | 10.0.0.2                         | Reserved for DNS in the subnet      |
| **Future Use**        | 10.0.0.3                         | Reserved by AWS for future features |
| **Broadcast Address** | 10.0.0.255                       | Cannot be assigned to an instance   |

# Key Point
Even though IPv4 doesnâ€™t use broadcast inside AWS VPC, the 5 reserved IP rule still applies.

# Usable IP Calculation in AWS Subnets
ðŸ”¹ Formula:
Usable IPs = (2^(32 â€“ CIDR)) â€“ 5
(because AWS reserves 5 IPs in every subnet)

| **CIDR Block** | **Total IPs** | **Reserved by AWS** | **Usable IPs** | **Example Subnet Range** |
| -------------- | ------------- | ------------------- | -------------- | ------------------------ |
| **/16**        | 65,536        | 5                   | **65,531**     | 10.0.0.0 â€“ 10.0.255.255  |
| **/20**        | 4,096         | 5                   | **4,091**      | 10.0.0.0 â€“ 10.0.15.255   |
| **/24**        | 256           | 5                   | **251**        | 10.0.0.0 â€“ 10.0.0.255    |
| **/28**        | 16            | 5                   | **11**         | 10.0.0.0 â€“ 10.0.0.15     |

# Example:
-> If you create a subnet with 10.0.1.0/24,
-> Total IPs = 256
-> AWS reserves 5 â†’ (10.0.1.0, 10.0.1.1, 10.0.1.2, 10.0.1.3, 10.0.1.255)
-> So, you can use 251 IPs for your EC2 instances, NAT, etc.

# What is Subnet
-> A subnet is a smaller network inside a VPC that divides the IP address range (CIDR block) of the VPC into smaller segments.
-> Subnets are associated with route tables that control how traffic flows within and outside the VPC.
-> Public subnets typically have a route to an Internet Gateway (IGW) to allow internet access for resources within the subnet.
-> Private subnets route traffic through a NAT Gateway to access the internet securely without exposing the resources directly.

# What is the difference between Public Subnet and Private Subnet

| Type               | Internet Access             | Typical Use                    | Gateway                                        |
| ------------------ | --------------------------- | ------------------------------ | ---------------------------------------------- |
| **Public Subnet**  |   Has internet access       | Web servers, Load balancers    | **Internet Gateway (IGW)**                     |
| **Private Subnet** |   No direct internet access | Databases, Application servers | **NAT Gateway** (for outbound internet access) |


# What is Internet Gateway (IGW)
-> Internet Gateway provides internet access to the public subnet inside a VPC.
-> It acts as a bridge between your VPC and the internet.
-> It supports two-way traffic, meaning it allows:
    Inbound traffic (from internet â†’ public subnet)
    Outbound traffic (from public subnet â†’ internet)

âœ… Key Point:
An Internet Gateway must be attached to your VPC and the public subnet route table must include a route like 0.0.0.0/0 â†’ IGW to enable internet access

# What is NAT Gateway (Network Address Translation Gateway)
-> NAT stands for Network Address Translation.
-> NAT Gateway allows instances in a private subnet to access the internet (for example, to download updates or reach external APIs).
-> It works as one-way traffic, meaning:
    Outgoing traffic: âœ… Allowed (Private â†’ Internet)
    Incoming traffic: âŒ Blocked (Internet â†’ Private)

ðŸ“˜ Note:
When a NAT Gateway is attached to a private subnet, it only allows outbound traffic from that subnet.
No one from the internet can directly access resources inside the private subnet


# Difference Between NACL and Security Group
ðŸ”¹ NACL (Network Access Control List)
-> Works at the Subnet Level.
-> Automatically applied when a subnet is created.
-> Stateless: You must manually define both Inbound and Outbound rules.
-> One subnet can have only one NACL attached.
-> You can create both Allow and Deny rules.

âœ… Example:
If you allow inbound traffic on port 80, you must manually allow outbound traffic on port 80 as well.

ðŸ”¹ Security Group (SG)
-> Works at the Instance Level (EC2, RDS, etc.).
-> You attach a Security Group manually to each resource.
-> Stateful: If you allow inbound traffic, the response traffic is automatically allowed outbound.
-> You can attach up to 5 Security Groups to a single instance.
-> You can create only Allow rules (no Deny rules).

âœ… Example:
If you allow inbound HTTP (port 80), the response will automatically be allowed outbound â€” no need to create a separate rule.

# How can you control the security to your VPC
-> you can use security group and NACL to control the security in VPC

# What are the Default Services We Get When We Create a Custom AWS VPC?

| Component                  | Description                                                                                                               |
| -------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Main Route Table**       | Automatically created and associated with all subnets by default. You can modify or create new route tables later.        |
| **Default Network ACL**    | Comes automatically with every VPC. It allows **all inbound and outbound traffic** by default.                            |
| **Default Security Group** | Automatically created for the VPC. It allows all traffic **within the same SG** and **denies all other inbound traffic**. |
| **DHCP Option Set**        | Automatically created to provide **DNS resolution** (usually uses AmazonProvidedDNS).                                     |
| **VPC CIDR Block**         | The IP range you specify while creating the VPC (e.g., 10.0.0.0/16).                                                      |

ðŸ”¸ Not Created by Default
-> You must create these manually after the VPC is created:
-> Subnets (Public/Private)
-> Internet Gateway (IGW)
-> NAT Gateway
-> Custom Route Tables (other than main)
-> Elastic IP (for NAT or public instances)

# How can you convert the public subnet to private subnet
-> Remove IGW and add NAT Gateway 

# What is Security group
-> Security allow you to control the traffic based on port , protocal and source/destination
-> AWS allow you to control the traffic in and out of your instance through firewall is called security group

# You have chosen a Windows instance with Classic networking, and you want to make some changes to the Security Group. How will these changes be effective?
-> Any changes made to the Security Group are automatically applied to the Windows instance.
-> You do not need to restart or stop the instance for the new rules to take effect.

# What is VPC peering connection
VPC Peering Connection allows you to connect one VPC to another VPC privately using AWSâ€™s internal network.

# To establish the peering connection between two VPC what conditions must be met
1. Non-Overlapping CIDR Blocks
    The IP address ranges (CIDR blocks) of both VPCs must not overlap.
    Example:
    VPC A â†’ 10.0.0.0/16
    VPC B â†’ 192.168.0.0/16
    âœ… Valid
    âŒ If both have 10.0.0.0/16 â†’ Peering not allowed.

2. Peering Can Be Established
-> Within the same region (Intra-region Peering).
-> Across different regions (Inter-region Peering).
-> Between different AWS accounts (Cross-account Peering).

3. Routing Configuration
-> After creating the peering connection, you must update the route tables in both VPCs to allow traffic to flow between them.

# what is VPC endpoint service
-> VPC Endpoint Service allows you to privately share your service (for example, an application running on EC2, ECS, or NLB) with other AWS accounts or VPCs without exposing it to the internet.
-> It uses the AWS PrivateLink feature to enable secure, private communication between VPCs.

ðŸ§  Simple Example
-> Suppose you have an application running on EC2 instances behind a Network Load Balancer (NLB) in Account A.
-> You want users in Account B (or another VPC) to access this service privately â€” without using the public internet.
-> You can create a VPC Endpoint Service in Account A, and Account B can create an Interface Endpoint to connect to it.


# What are the Types of VPC Endpoints

1ï¸âƒ£ Interface Endpoint
-> It creates an elastic network interface (ENI) in your subnet with a private IP address.
-> Used to connect privately to most AWS services, third-party services, or your own custom services (via PrivateLink).
-> It supports ~86+ AWS services such as EC2, SSM, CloudWatch, SNS, SQS, etc.
-> Works over AWS PrivateLink.

âœ… Example:
Connect to ssm.amazonaws.com or sns.amazonaws.com privately via an Interface Endpoint.

2ï¸âƒ£ Gateway Endpoint
-> Used to connect to specific AWS services through a gateway target in your route table.
-> Supports only two AWS services:
  Amazon S3
  Amazon DynamoDB
-> Does not create an ENI, instead it updates the route table to send traffic to the service privately.

âœ… Example:
When you create a Gateway Endpoint for S3, your EC2 instance in the private subnet can access S3 without an Internet Gateway or NAT Gateway.

3ï¸âƒ£ Gateway Load Balancer Endpoint (GLB Endpoint)
-> Used to connect to third-party virtual appliances such as firewalls, intrusion detection, or monitoring tools hosted behind a Gateway Load Balancer (GWLB).
-> It enables transparent traffic inspection between VPCs using PrivateLink.
-> Ideal for network security and inspection use cases.

âœ… Example:
Send inbound/outbound traffic through a firewall appliance hosted in another VPC using a Gateway Load Balancer Endpoint.

# What is the Virtual Network Interface That You Can Attach to an Instance in a VPC?
-> The virtual network interface that you can attach to an instance in a VPC is called a Network Interface or Elastic Network Interface (ENI).

âœ… Key Points
-> ENI is a virtual network card for your EC2 instance inside a VPC.
-> Every EC2 instance has a primary network interface by default.
-> You can also attach additional ENIs to the same instance (depending on instance type).
-> Each ENI can have:
    A Private IP address
    A Public IP (optional)
    One or more Security Groups
    A MAC address
    A Subnet association

# When Attached to an Amazon VPC, Which Two Components Provide Connectivity with External Networks?
-> The two components that provide connectivity with external networks are:
    1. Internet Gateway (IGW)
    2. NAT Gateway

# What is NAT instance
-> A NAT Instance is an EC2 instance used to enable internet access for private subnet resources, allowing outbound-only communication while blocking inbound traffic

âœ… Key Points
Itâ€™s an EC2 instance running in a public subnet.
Private instances send traffic to the NAT instance, which forwards requests to the internet and returns responses.
It allows outbound connections (e.g., software updates, API calls) but blocks inbound connections from the internet.
You must configure route tables to send private subnet traffic to the NAT instance.
AWS provides a preconfigured AMI called â€œAmazon NAT AMIâ€.

# What is VPN
-> VPN Stands for Virtual private Network
-> VPN will create the tunnel between Server and Client to access the data securely over the internet.

# What is DHCP
-> DHCP stands for Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol.
-> It is a network management protocol used to automatically assign IP addresses and other network configuration settings such as subnet mask, default gateway, and DNS server to devices on a network.
-> This helps devices communicate on the network without manually configuring IP settings.
-> Port Numbers:
    UDP Port 67 â†’ used by the DHCP Server
    UDP Port 68 â†’ used by the DHCP Client



# What is IAM
-> IAM Stands for Identity and Access Management (IAM) that helps us securely control access to AWS resources. 
-> With IAM, you can manage users, groups, roles, and policies to ensure that the right permissions are assigned to the right entities.

# What is IAM User
-> An IAM User is an identity within AWS that represents a person or an application that needs to interact with AWS resources.

# What is IAM User Groups
-> An IAM User Group is a collection of IAM users. The permissions assigned to the group are inherited by all users within that group.

# What is IAM Roles
-> IAM role is unlike IAM user to interact with AWS resources but roles do not have permanent credentials. It rely on temporary security credentials

# What is IAM Policies
-> An IAM Policy is a JSON document that defines the permissions granted to an IAM user, group, or role. 
-> Policies have 2 types of policies
   -> Managed Policies
   -> Inline policies

# What is the difference between role and policy
Simplified Example
Role Example:
â€œAllow EC2 instance to read data from S3â€ â†’ You create a role with an S3 read-only policy and attach it to the EC2 instance.

Policy Example:
â€œAllow a user to manage S3 bucketsâ€ â†’ You create a policy granting s3:* permissions and attach it to a specific IAM user or group.

# What are the two types of access that you can provide when you creating the user
1. Programmatic Access
-> Used for: Command-line tools, SDKs, and API calls.
-> Credentials: AWS provides
		Access Key ID
		Secret Access Key
-> Use case example:
     A developer or application uses the AWS CLI or SDK to upload files to an S3 bucket or start EC2 instances.
     Example Tools: AWS CLI, AWS SDK, Terraform, Python (boto3).

2. AWS Management Console Access
-> Used for: Signing in to the AWS web console (GUI).
-> Credentials:
	Username and Password (you can also enable MFA for security).
-> Use case example:
    An administrator or developer logs into the AWS Console to create and manage resources visually.


# I am viewing aws console but unable to launch the instance, i recive IAM error how can i rectify it
-> I need to give ec2 permission to that IAM user

# I dont want my AWS account id to be exposed to users how can i avoid it
-> Yes â€” by default, AWS gives every account a sign-in URL that includes your 12-digit AWS account ID, like this:
		https://123456789012.signin.aws.amazon.com/console
-> We can create a custom alias for your AWS account in the IAM console, which replaces your account ID in the login URL.
